## Host options (pick one)

### GitHub Pages

1. Push repo to GitHub.
2. **Settings → Pages →** Build from branch/folder: select branch and **`/docs/site`** as folder (or use `gh-pages` branch containing only `docs/site` contents).
3. If GitHub serves from project site `https://user.github.io/repo/`, either set **site root** to that subpath in Pages settings (so `index.html` is at repo root of the Pages branch) **or** add `<base href="/repo-name/">` in each HTML file—simplest is a **dedicated branch** or **workflow** that copies `docs/site/*` to the root of `gh-pages`.
4. Custom domain: add `CNAME` file in published root + DNS records per GitHub docs.

### Cloudflare Pages

1. Connect Git repo; set **build command** empty, **output directory** `docs/site` (or build command `exit 0` and root `docs/site`).
2. Attach custom domain in Cloudflare dashboard; SSL automatic.

### Netlify

1. New site from Git; **publish directory** `docs/site`.
2. No build command required.
3. Domain: Netlify DNS or external CNAME.

### Any VPS / shared hosting (FTP/SFTP)

1. Upload contents of `docs/site/` (not the parent `docs/` folder) into `public_html/` or subdirectory.
2. Ensure `index.html` is the default document.

### Amazon S3 + CloudFront (advanced)

1. Sync `docs/site/` to a bucket; enable static website hosting; CloudFront for HTTPS and custom domain.

## Post-publish checklist

- [ ] HTTPS everywhere; HTTP → HTTPS redirect.
- [ ] Favicon (add `favicon.ico` later if desired).
- [ ] Submit sitemap to search consoles (optional; small site).
- [ ] Tag a git release noting “documentation site live at …”.
